And the wall collapsed …
Here's a quiz for history enthusiasts: twenty years ago, the year 1989 was a fateful year marked by three events that all took place on June 4.
Which one do you remember the best and which one had the heaviest consequences for the planet?
a) The bloody repression of Tiananmen Square
b) The death of Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran
c) The elections in Poland
Few people answer c).
Because the events in Beijing and the death of Khomeini which made headlines eclipsed the victory of the famous opposition union Solidarity during the first free election in Eastern Europe since 1946.
Yet, nothing contributed more to the collapse of communism in Europe - and consequently to the refounding of the post-war international order.
There will be all sorts of commemorations of the end of communism in the coming months, notably the anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989.
For many people it was a moment of glory, emblematic of the Western victory at the end of the Cold War, a victory that came from who knows where.
But by having attended the collapse of the Eastern bloc from the beginning, we realize that the process was long and complex.
The election in Poland was a point of no return, the moment when the movement in favor of change became irreversible.
It had gained strength after a summer of strikes, when the communist leader at the head of Poland, the General Jaruzelski, estimated that the country's economic problems were too severe for him to face alone.
Why not call on the Polish opposition, he thought - if not to find a solution - at least to make them share the responsibility of the situation?
After six months of bargaining, it concluded a historical agreement: there would be free and fair legislative elections and Solidarity would be able to participate in them.
The communist leaders (no more than Solidarity) had not envisioned for a single instant that they could lose.
Even in their darkest nightmares, they did not imagine that they were going to be ousted from power.
Yet, that is what happened.
Looking back, it is astonishing that there could have been any doubts.
Solidarnosc campaigned brazenly.
A famous poster, borrowed for the occasion from a great western classic, The Train Will Be at Station Three Times, was a huge success: it showed Gary Cooper with a ballot box in hand instead of a revolver, playing the role of the sheriff.
June 4 was Judgment Day.
On that bright Sunday morning, while spring was giving birth to summer, the voters sent the Polish communists to the slaughterhouse.
For their last day in power, the Polish communists resorted to one final perversity which turned into an involuntary act of self-humiliation.
They had designed an electoral system in which the Poles, instead of selecting their preferred candidates, had to strike out the names of those they did not want - in short, all the communists listed on the ballots.
Everywhere you looked, people were getting rid of the detested autocrats.
This was finally the popular uprising that Poland had been waiting for, the revenge for December 1980, when Jaruzelski had declared martial law, banned Solidarnosc and thrown its leaders in prison.
The revolution with a pen!
Handled with style, the pen that finally won out over the sword, becomes the weapon of a glorious revenge.
Certain voters were tearing up their ballots outright, thus toppling the old regime with a single effective blow.
Others savored the moment, perhaps taking a drag on a cigarette while crossing out names on the ballots.
"That one put my cousin in prison", Pfft!, "As for that apparatchik, he's gotten rich off our poverty", Pfft!
Pfft!
On the other hand, the communist campaign went almost unnoticed.
In all of Warsaw, only two government candidates bothered to put up posters.
Most of them were counting on their monopoly in the media to get their message across: "Vote for Lezek, a good communist".
We can say to their credit that the regime recognized its defeat with remarkable graciousness.
The day after the elections, at three o'clock in the afternoon, Jaruzelski gathered the main party officials to tell them: "Our defeat is total", we must find a political solution".
He meant that he did not want either violence or fraud, the communists would have to live with the result of the vote.
Twenty years on, I'm still perplexed.
Those of us covering Eastern Europe at the time knew Solidarity would win.
We also knew that this peaceful victory would be an example for the rest of Eastern Europe.
The election in Poland was extremely encouraging for anti-communists all around the world.
Thanks to Poland, what had seemed impossible just a few days before suddenly became achievable.
There had been other signs.
In May, the Hungarian reformers began to dismantle the grills erected on the border with Austria - a hole in the Iron Curtain.
In Moscow, Mikhail Gorbachev spoke of a "Common European Home" and rejected the Brezhnev doctrine of interventionism.
However, when the wall fell, political leaders and experts uniformly acknowledged: "We saw nothing coming".
The Cold War lasted so long that any change seemed impossible - until the freedom burst forth.
